Prague Stock Exchange plunged to a minus at the end of trading
After a sharp fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the normal daily trade.
The Prague Stock Exchange has followed up on its Monday decline since the beginning of trading on Tuesday, when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, the stock market is falling on Wall Street.
Even in our country, the market’s reaction to the result of the vote of the U.S. House of Representatives, which refused to support the plan to stabilize the local financial sector.
The fall of shares in Asia
Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic crash on Tuesday, although indices eventually wiped out some of the losses over the course of the day.
Hong Kong’s Hang Seng Index took almost 4% off during trading, but later erased some of the losses and reduced the drop to around 2.5%.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, in Shanghai the markets were closed.
Sydney shares lost more than five percent, but eventually fell to 4.3 percent.
Taiwan’s stock market fell 3.6 percent, according to the index.
“The timing of the rescue operation in the U.S. is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, despite being part of China, sets its monetary policy independently, i.e. without dependence on the Chinese central bank.
Hong Kong has the same interest rates as the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said lawmakers should return to negotiations and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Other countries are also at risk of being affected.
A Bloodbath of American Shares
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was expected to cost as much as $700 billion.
The lawmakers ignored President George W. Bush’s call to back the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks suffered a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices saw their biggest crash in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell nearly seven percent, with the most recent decline on a similar scale in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the proposal had not passed in the House, the index found itself in free fall.
Congress backs down: U.S. government can pump $700 billion into banks
U.S. Congressional leaders and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the U.S. financial system.
It will be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks to approve a $700 billion bailout for the U.S. financial system.
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen must finalize some details of the deal before they can publish the bill and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
The Senate may vote on the plan on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that a rescue plan would be approved should be the first major psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
Then, however, there will be a "sobering up" due to the complexity of the mechanisms by which markets can be helped in practice as well.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We’ve settled our differences about what a market stabilization package looks like,” said Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat.
He said the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give a definitive shape to the government fund.
It should buy unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which pull financial companies into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Signal for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis is having a major impact on the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
Senator Harry Reid, a Democrat from Nevada, said lawmakers are working to reach a final agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone where Congress’s decision could affect Monday’s trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two houses of Congress will vote on the bill, nor whether they can hold talks at the last minute on a problem.
Legislators hope it will be approved in the next few days.
However, the law will make a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the scheme is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush has demanded.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels the program is failing to fulfill its function, in a sequence of another $100 billion, and later the final $350 billion.
Bush applauds progress in negotiations
The president can veto the decision, but Congress can override it.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to raise funds to buy bad mortgage securities, whose value has plummeted because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, has remained.
“We worked out everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
US President Bush is also pleased with the progress of the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and praised "the two-part effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Restrictions on gold parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the lead negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed to be responsible for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing concessions, timing of funding the plan.
The new law will also restrict the so-called gold parachutes for company directors participating in the program, and set up a committee to oversee the fund.
It should be run by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard and made great progress towards a deal that will work and be useful for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also counts on help for homeowners who are having trouble paying back.
The government should negotiate new installments on the mortgages it buys in order to reduce the monthly cost of installments for borrowers and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological support
According to chief economist David Mark, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
“This is because we don’t know what the mechanism is and at what price the distressed assets will be bought.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government share their losses," Marek told news server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be approved now or at the beginning of next week is not so important, according to Mark.
"It is much more important that the congressmen agree this week that they support this plan and that they will consecrate it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on the approval is the most important at the moment," Marek stressed.
Battle on the knife edge: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It seems to me that it is better to just buy a phone.
However, there are plenty of reasons to get a separate player.
The choice entirely depends on the method of use and the demands of the future owner.
It’s hard to get a high-end record player to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
On the one hand, such music products are not based on LPs and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if you have vinyls with art rock, jazz or blues on your shelves, you probably dream of such a turntable at least.
It is the same with music on the go, i.e. music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
It may be unacceptable for someone to spend eight thousand crowns on the player, just as a Pink Floyd fan will hardly bite the headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life.
Some top music players can do much more than just play music, but what most mobiles do not even happen.
No other device is as versatile as a phone.
In addition to primary functions, telephony and texting, it can play music and video, record both, has a better, worse camera and can even navigate.
And taking into account smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph anything.
The versatility of mobile also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the display will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Hardly any cell phone can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, expect that they will not play for more than a few hours.
If you still call now and then, get one more charger to work for sure - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players you will not have this problem, even the worst will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem arises when recording music on mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
With the exception of iPods, you do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players already create their own music library sorted by artist name, album name, genre or user rating.
Some devices display only the tree structure of directories similar to Windows Explorer, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with an operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobiles are more capable
When choosing a particular device, be particularly interested in battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output, and, of course, comfort of operation.
If your music is primarily a backdrop and you listen to it every day for a short time, for example, in a tram, you just need any mobile phone that plays MP3.
Almost any cell phone can do that.
You don’t even have to look too closely at what music formats your phone or player can do.
MP3 can handle all of them, and the vast majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely used and besides it, the vast majority of devices can handle music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also make it possible to buy music online, for example.
Just visit the relevant website of the operator (or other provider) and buy a song or album via the mobile internet.
This service itself could be a strong argument for the acquisition of a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is lousy and is mostly limited to fast-fermented radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (via GSM, internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their mobiles with them.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you can feel the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least wired handsfree.
If not, you can use the integrated speaker, which has almost every mobile, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music mobiles will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than $3,000.
For three and four thousand crowns you will get a very decent walkman.
However, most of the time you will be limited by the absence of output on ordinary headphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones even with a 3.5 mm socket for conventional headphones cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can handle really everyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of the control with the previously common cassette player or turntable is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mistakenly turned on mobile internet and subsequently a giant account for data transmission.
What device to touch
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the appropriate card, you can fit into two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive can handle 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, go for Cowon, Creativa, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, opt for specialized mobile phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and thus the comfort of operation is closer to a separate MP3 player.
The furthest in the industry is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series phones have the same user interface as separately sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), MP3 players will take you away from the above-mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer practically all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, something is missing here - a virtual operator that would make the classic ones cheaper.
Maybe he won't be long.
We have written about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe on Mobil.cz many times.
This was also confirmed by ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really like to get into the fight.
It may sound paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and penetration well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ), has often pointed out that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classical operator with its own network probably does not have much chance (after all, it would be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, to which classical operators also had to respond.
Even before the introduction of pikes such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the market, similar voices were heard in the UK as in our country.
However, it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator has managed to reach more than 100,000 customers and become the country’s fifth largest operator.
The financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, U:fona in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - offering cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a bet on a new target group can also be a pretty good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"The right guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could catch on in our country.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone’s press secretary, doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segmented approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the financial group Penta, said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything they can to prevent any potential competitor from emerging.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been hidden for a long time by the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in offering our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them," said Pavel Kaidl, press spokesperson for the group.
So maybe it’s time for better days.
From the unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator is expected by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room for a full-fledged virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any subject with a complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2 told Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokesperson for T-Mobile, said: “We have not yet seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which we can build further.”
He added: “By the end of the year, it will be difficult for any virtual operator to appear on T-Mobile’s network.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table to be able to think in this short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "By negotiating with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, lead to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when operators want something, they can pull together is evidenced by the scramble around the creation of U:fona.
Probably the biggest pressure towards CTU came at the time of the creation of U:fona from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the CTU website.
However, U:fon is now useful as an argument for not allowing a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and especially on his services."
Given this approach of mobile operators, however, the complete lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is striking.
It is not just CTU's position, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
However, he took a typical position on the whole issue.
"The virtual operator's entry into the mobile market would be possible after a contract was concluded between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential candidates was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the Office of the Czech Republic said in response to our question.
It is not surprising that such a statement is made by the operators.
It is more than reasonable for an authority to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position in the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: “In foreign countries, where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in prices for mobile telephone services.”
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices is clearly not one of the interests of the Office.
In fact, what is shocking about the whole case is the touching harmony of the three mobile operators that results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is just a coincidence is entirely self-evident.
Just like the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is certainly just a matter of chance and fierce competition.
"The Office did not find any signs of anti-competitive conduct in this matter and therefore has no reason to interfere in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have a correspondingly increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools to open the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to be lacking even to the telecommunication regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of a dominant market position is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are the only market in terms of competition.
Of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - to create a virtual operator, the consent of the network operator is always required.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment it must necessarily be dominant.
Even if we do not allow this argument, it should at least be a warning for the Office that three mobile operators are acting in a strikingly similar way.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
Blaming responsibilities on CTU is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications, which the Office puts its hands away from the whole matter.
We have met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, CTÚ’s powers in the area of competition in telecommunications were not able to be enforced, although many experts had hoped to improve the situation.
That’s something that people need to know more about, but it seems to be their interests elsewhere.
It happens when no one is looking.
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies issuing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile telephone services.
The prices of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic business customer to the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, you will receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar reselling.
"If there were cases that you are talking about, it could be a violation of the terms and conditions that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Kemrová said.
However, it is unlikely that such activity will not reach the responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators opposes such a procedure.
They make significant profits from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to the possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they can not fully dispose of it as normal customers of mobile operators."
That’s what should be weird at least.
In addition, another question arises for the Office.
If mobile operators are turning a blind eye to a similar process, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the Office has relatively strong powers to reveal similar activities, and if it does not want to, it may not be satisfied with the operators’ explanation that they have no idea about this and their terms and conditions prohibit it.
When will we not be the most expensive
As has been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable decrease in prices for services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, regulators have intervened at this very moment to defend not the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they have achieved that the first virtual operator was created and others have flocked to it.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are shifting the case like a hot potato.
From our experience, we can not get rid of the impression that the lack of competence in these cases more than suits them.
But let's not waste any more time.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator is coming to us really soon, the Czech mobile market may be starting up again.
If any of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the Office to remain indifferent to rejecting (discrimination) other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The Czech national anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to four versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem Where Is My Home on the occasion of the Czech Statehood Day.
The anthem was newly recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions - with male or female solo singing, in choral performance and instrumental version.
The song was sung by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the adaptations of the anthem are Otakar Jeremias and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on iHNed.cz.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymen.
He had previously told Czech Radio that he had deliberately chosen singers with young, representative voices to sing solo.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both of them and the choir had a clear diction, that the text was well understood, that they resonated," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where is My Home was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the Estates Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously took it for their own.
After the establishment of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
