Prague Public Transport will ride on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will go down in the history of the Prague Public Transit Company as the date when the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who will have an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At the moment, it can be purchased by about 100,000 people who own an Opencard smart card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day and annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and have it uploaded to their smart card at the information centres and workplaces of the Transport Company in the metro stations Muzeum, Mustek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Since yesterday, coupons can also be purchased via the Internet on the website of Dopravní podnik www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers in the afternoon.
Those who start using the e-shop can definitely forget about the dispensing windows in the metro stations, where they have had to regularly stand in long lines for paper tickets.
They buy the coupon online and put it on their Opencard in one of the 13 branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places, passengers are provided with a desk with trained staff that will help those interested with online shopping and will also upload the purchased coupon to their card," said Martin Opatrný, spokesperson for the project.
In addition to libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic coupons to Opencard also in self-service vending machines, which are mounted in several metro vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket markers and passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," said Opatrný.
The coupon will check the driver’s seat with a vending machine
Operation of the machines, which will start to work tomorrow, is simple.
Just insert an Opencard chip into them and the previously paid coupon will upload to it itself.
Electronic coupons from tomorrow apply not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
That is, in suburban trains and bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, which go to the capital mainly residents of Central Bohemian municipalities.
"In trains included in the Prague Integrated Transport, conductors are equipped with card readers to determine the time and zone validity of coupons," explained Filip Drápal, of the Ropid organization, which compiles timetables for Prague public transport.
Suburban buses have card readers built into the cash register of the driver.
When boarding, it is necessary not only to show the smart card to the driver, but also to attach the Opencard to the designated place on the side of the cash register.
This way the driver will check the validity of the uploaded coupons.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the recorded coupons, there is nothing easier than to ask the driver for this information," added Drápal.
Passengers who do not ride suburban buses and do not remember when their coupon expires can head back to the self-service vending machines, where the coupons on the card are recorded.
Here, information about the validity of their documents is displayed on the device display.
The Sudetenland wanted a referendum.
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans asked for the incorporation of Šumava into the United States.
It follows from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Science Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the patronage of the United States of America.
It is said that in 1945 some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the President of the United States.
This follows, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Science Library.
The Germans in Český Krumlov are asking the US president not to allow the "Sumava County" - taken by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
“We have understood the situation correctly, and we want to be really sure in words that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” the letter reads, signed with the words “People who care about the fate of Šumava.”
Since joining Czechoslovakia supposedly gives Sudeten Germans - with knowledge of the Czech national character - hope only for brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter to the American president ask that he take over the protectorate over Šumava for the present and eternal times.
"We cannot believe that you, regardless of the opinion of a quarter of a million people, would give this territory to a foreign state that oppresses and disproves minorities and nothing but nothing to contribute to the victory of the Allies," the letter said.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of the vengefulness of "Czech oppressors".
