Even rats have feelings.
When a rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean that they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals have feelings.
But how can they be verified to feel the same when they behave like us?
The online magazine "Edge" has been publishing the contributions of well-known scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in its series presents selected answers to the question "What do you consider to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it, when we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we start dealing with a different kind and open up the issues of perception or consciousness in general, we enter an impassable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it will do what many other animals do: pretend to be dead, flee, or attack.
Humans behave in a similar way, from which some scientists infer a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe in that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to the experience of animals.
This is partly because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always involve the prefrontal cortex (because of its contribution to short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This large area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and appears to be completely absent from other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, between knowing who we are and being able to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that man is different even from other primates.
Another dramatic feature could be the linguistic nature of man: because so much of his perception is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude the animals.
But even if language did not matter, language would certainly influence it, so animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably be different from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to find out what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, we cannot even measure ourselves on the basis of our own experience, for the sake of special hardware, we are faced with great problems in exploring it.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach by Christof Koch and Francis Crick focuses on the neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but perhaps they are not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of a non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I deduce them from the fact that the emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of a defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as body reactions) utilizes operational memory.
Seen from this angle, the sensations are closely intertwined with those areas of the cortex that are characteristic of primates, and especially humans.
In connection with linguistic nature, a fine gradation of perception arises, because by means of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states in order to attribute them to others alongside ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in areas of the cortex and brain stem devoted to body sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much over the course of human evolution, it could well be involved in the sensations perceived by multiple animal genera.
In theory, I can’t argue with that, but I think it’s unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to be felt by both organisms in the same way: But how is it possible to verify, says Pankseep, whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
The cockroach flees from danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the conformity of experiencing.
It’s true that neural comparisons take us further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, while cockroaches and brains do.
But is the brain stem responsible for the feelings?
And even if it could be proved in man: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are likely to be fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness rests on special circuits and language), I prefer to examine emotional behavior rather than the emotional perception of rats.
Anyway, in this case, we can see progress at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
As with rats, I do not examine language and consciousness, nor do I examine feelings, after all, I do not know if they exist.
It may be considered short-sighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than throw myself against the wall repeatedly.
I am a practical emotionalist.
