The Bilingual Debate: Immersion in English
In this issue of Focused on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss candidates' attitudes toward bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a California academic and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, co-authored the book "Worse Than You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose Schools".
Effectively reaching out to Hispanic voters is a tricky matter.
Barack Obama’s educational agenda proves it.
The Obama campaign notes that "African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students," which is true.
To combat such performance gaps, Obama’s education agenda advocates, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for those who are still learning English.
But the question remains whether Barack Obama’s commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes using languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in reducing performance gaps.
Take Sixth Street Prep, a charter primary school in Los Angeles East.
The majority of the students at this school are Hispanics from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
Even so, a whopping one hundred percent of fourth-grade students reached the highest level in state math tests in 2008.
Almost as amazing ninety-three percent of fourth graders got to the highest level in state tests of English language and literature.
This incredible achievement has been achieved by a method other than the one Obama favors.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of abilities, and access without excuses.
Further, and this Obama should note, is, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school's pedagogical approach for those just learning English, "complete immersion."
Immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, "We had tremendous success with one completely new pupil from Mexico - after twelve months you would walk into a classroom and not know which one it was."
"It works," she said, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for what other schools with large proportions of Hispanic and English-taught students should look like?
The results achieved by the school should be taken for granted in answering this question, but the educational agenda of his own party (the National Education Association is a long-time proponent of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make prediction of Obama’s answer unclear.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the matter when he said that people should stop worrying about "only English" laws.
Instead, "you should make sure your children speak Spanish," he said.
If Obama really wants to erase performance differences, he should think carefully about educational patterns that work, rather than mocking them and trivializing them.
