The wild ride in the second quarter broke the team's record
After spending more time in the Jets than anyone else over the past eight seasons, defensive player Shaun Ellis thought he’d seen it all.
He then followed the development of the second quarter on Sunday, in which the Jets turned a scoreless game into a spanking ride.
“I’ve never seen anything like it,” Ellis said.
The second quarter began after the Jets and the Arizona Cardinals matched each other in a bleak game.
Then quarterback Brett Favre sent Laveranues Coles on a 12-yard touchdown sprint, perfectly foreshadowing an afternoon in which their gradually developing collaboration moved miles ahead.
Favre sent Coles in that quarter behind two more touchdowns, including the one in which cornerback fell, and another 10 seconds before half-match.
"It was nothing special," Favre told Coles of all his passes.
"He's a damn good player.
We were very good at communicating, no matter what people think.”
While Favre and Coles were tossing, the defense attacked Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner.
Cornerback Darelle Revis caught a stray throw and returned it 32 yards for a touchdown.
Safety Eric Smith picked up another pass and caught it.
Linebacker David Bowens forced Warner to fumble.
The last loss of the ball, the fumble that Bowens forced, was perhaps the best ever.
The Cardinals got to the ball 10 seconds before the end, and after the Jets recovered the ball, Jay Feely kicked a twenty-yard goal from the field, thus gaining a 34-0 lead.
That's the most the Jets have ever won in a quarter.
Jets coach Eric Mangini, when asked to describe the madness, said, "Second quarter, or third quarter?"
When he was told that both - the Jets allowed 21 points in the third quarter with no answer - Mangini said, "I can tell you that I enjoyed the second quarter much more than the third.
Many points were scored in a short period of time."
Retired Gebreselassie improved his world record
Haile Gebreselassie from Ethiopia once again showed why many consider him the best long-distance runner ever, having broken his own world record in the Berlin Marathon on Sunday, becoming the first person to run a 26.2-mile race under two hours and four minutes.
By winning on a pleasantly flat track in a time of 2:03:59, he topped by 27 seconds his previous time of 2:04:26, which he ran last year in Berlin.
Gebreselassie, who is 35, has set the 26th world record of his career, which is really incredibly wide - he broke the world record or at least is the world champion at all distances from a metric mile to a marathon.
Last month, Gebreselassie missed the Olympic marathon in Beijing because he was afraid - perhaps too scared in retrospect - that air pollution would irritate his asthma problems.
Instead, he promised to run in Berlin.
In almost perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish - Gebreselassie won on Sunday with a lightning fast average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
With runners like Gebreselassie and Paul Tergat from Kenya focusing on longer runs, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes over the past decade, since Ronaldo da Costa from Brazil won Berlin in 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday's victory, Gebreselassie told reporters he had calf cramps two weeks ago and missed a week of training.
Clearly, the break was more of a wake-up call than a hold-up.
"I'm so happy," Gebreselassie told reporters.
"Everything was perfect.
I started again a week ago and I was a little bit in doubt today, but everything was fine."
He was also criticized - especially in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - for allegedly over-planning his races, generally avoiding world marathon tops, relying on drivers as if it were a race on the track, and setting world records above a sense of competition.
But this criticism can hardly reduce Gebreselassie's huge running qualities.
Maintained at a pace by four Kenyans, Gebreselassie reached the half by a time of 1:02:04.
After the drivers dropped out, Gebreselassie was constantly chased by two elite Kenyan runners James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi.
A little earlier than three miles before the finish, Gebreselassie took his last run and escaped Kwambai, who then finished in second place in 2:05:36, improving his personal maximum by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in a time of 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a German citizen, finished the excellent year with the seventh fastest time in history 2:19:19.
The record time of 2:15:25 is held by Paula Radcliffe from Great Britain.
36-year-old Mikitenko won the London Marathon in 2:24:14 time last spring.
She missed the Beijing Games due to what has been described as a back injury, but recovered and won in Berlin and in the third marathon she ever ran, she improved her personal maximum by almost five minutes.
She ran the race smartly and thoughtfully: she let four Ethiopian and Kenyan female runners escape to a big lead and then she made it after about 18 1/2 miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa from Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31 and Helene Kiprop from Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
Proudness and Obstacles to Black Life in a Separate City
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of Greater Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy and huge, lies a quiet city in which the pride and pretentiousness of African-American life comes to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet courses, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of guavas, two schools, and no jail."
Now it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville Festival to pay their respects to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains sidelined, though she made it a stop for tourists by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers Project from the Depression.
It is still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year in which the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for open discussion about race, many residents remain wary of alien views.
“We pay a lot of attention to how our story is told,” says Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the city’s oldest parish.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and exertion.
It is both a historical model of black ascension and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also an oak tree-shadowed example of Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes lauded - that arose out of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the locals are both proud and protective.
And the worry about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way Hurston is called here.
She introduced the world to her hometown through heartfelt books full of dialects such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of a Florida tourist guide turned the city a short way into Route 17, which leads through the often ephemeral center of Florida, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With a big drum in life and in literature, Hurston took the reader to the store of the first Eatonville mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"The left side of the road," she wrote, "is a white brown-trimmed modern national school with well-kept yards and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even if he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned widow Dash's new husband, writing that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything at all that fits into an hour-long hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston has linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
This was clearly not the typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it wasn't a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it the way it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the choruses Johnson's girls made immortal by quoting men singing dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered as a chipper eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time, when she rushed into the city, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is still proud of dignified dress today.
Most of the residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many sneered.
"People have always loved seeing Zora," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging in a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely christened, "she never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Eatonville, along with the rest of the world, seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major funeral ceremonies or major public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood its significance to the world or its legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's "Wrapped in Rainbows," published in 2003.
Change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to stretch the city's five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is the local two-lane main road.
The sprawl of Orlando has already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still coming out of a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the race-mixing struggle brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At the time, a bunch of white guys, they came in and threw oranges and stuff at people sitting on the side," Franklin said.
“Actually, there was a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration and stated of his decision in the Brown case against the Chamber of Education that it was "insulting rather than glorifying to my race."
Residents now argue that desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of its youth.
"Black children were used to hugs - I remember that - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You don't hug your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there's a cultural barrier," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped make room for many other Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors, and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with reckless self-confidence and quotes such as "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker reached the unmarked grave of Hurston and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, a eulogized biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway came on shelves in bookstores, re-enrolling her into the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville's most famous daughter had found the ramp lights again.
Hurston's former neighbors now considered her a savior.
To show what can happen with its highway to destroy, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return to celebrate.
After several years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"The five currents of the highway have resurrected, you would say, directly detonated, real civic pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply: "The dawn saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped change the city's image.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the church in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to reassess the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the re-asphalted and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes act as a backwater alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Ninety percent are black.)
Strangers who come in search of the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Permission for most conversations must be given in advance, and certain things - like the murals in Eatonville's oldest church, painted by whites and depicting blacks in the fields - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a courageous, self-assured teacher who likes deep red, still fear that their isolated community will not be understood properly.
And even as the Hurston Festival has grown, so has the domestic pride.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems and all that, but no better, no worse, and just as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish, and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
From the voice of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, resounds a heartfelt love for the community as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or police force, which he says would use some help.
And even younger ones, such as the 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“Most people, when they just pass through here, think, ‘Hm, this town is nothing compared to the others,’” Alondra Kenon said recently after church.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a while, it's a very nice city."
Here in New York, we're all fluent in finance.
At first glance, nothing has changed here.
If tourists in Manhattan had stayed away from newsstands and huge television screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t have realized they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never guess that in the glass beehive of offices above their heads, every day the bankers and investment fund managers who monopolize New York have the worst "bad day in the office" since the 1929 crisis.
The messengers are still rattling metal carts along the sidewalks, transporting muffin pans to breakfast meetings.
Hispanics still move between the towers and wear, like human mules, fifty ironed shirts that hang from the braces on their backs.
Office rats are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at street food stalls, and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi between 4 and 7 p.m. on a weekday.
It didn’t look like a crisis at all, until I decided, with all my pessimism, to open a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I had timed this assignment to coincide with the late afternoon siesta at my local JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about twenty people waiting in line.
Not in front of checkout windows to pick up or deposit cash, but in front of a counter where older clients order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to the Macy's convenience store, and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker," came for the same reason I did.
However, they have already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in places they have come from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, or Staten Island.
They have withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (a bit like building savings banks), money unions, and those types of savings banks whose branches operate in only one state and which claim to treat their customers like family.
In the past year, 15 such banks have quietly gone bankrupt.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and when New Yorkers were coming home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, tried to hunt down a rescue buyer.
The employees of the offices and shops who stood in front of me and were afraid of another collapse were moving their cash to a bank that is perceived as a safe haven and that does most of the saving on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned to be fluent in finance over the past week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket spoke on the phone and spoke to Lehman Borthers, the bankrupt bank, and her emaciated chief executive, Dick Fuld, with the familiarity of gossiping about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed, roughly 50-year-old housekeeper of my apartment building, changed the subject of our ordinary conversation - Brad, Angelina, or my grocery delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me, "I now have my savings in money market funds.
I moved it, I won't risk it."
Muslim graves desecrated after Austrian right-wing rupture
Heinz-Christian Strache, on the left, from the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party, and Filip Dewinter from the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party are taking part in a demonstration that presented the organization "Cities against Islamization" in Antwerp on Thursday, 17 January 2008.
They carry signs similar to traffic signs that depict mosques crossed by a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend, in which far-right parties made huge gains in the general election.
More than 90 graves in the cemetery in the town of Traun near Linz were badly damaged sometime between Friday evening and this morning, and police are convinced that it was an organized event.
The culprits spray-painted Jewish symbols on some of the graves, such as the Star of David, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to disguise extremists’ motives of hatred for Muslim immigrants.
It is unclear whether this incident was in any way linked to the election.
A spokesman for the Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by reports of desecration coming as the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan nears its end.
Meanwhile, Austria enters the soul-searching round after a swing to the right in yesterday’s parliamentary election.
The two far-right parties, which together garnered more than 30 percent of the vote, the Freedom Party and the Union for the Future of Austria, led a vehemently anti-immigration campaign, and some of their slogans were denounced by critics as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, leader of the Freedom Party, which received over 18 percent of the vote, campaigned against headscarves and burqas, and even voiced his opposition to foods that are perceived to have a relationship with Islam.
In a recent meeting with voters in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both sides are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses carried out immediately after the elections, which put the extreme right in the position of the country's strongest political bloc, suggest that this change was mainly caused by young voters worrying about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is not allowed to travel abroad.
Gary Glitter, a glamrock star convicted of child sexual abuse, was banned from travelling to France and Spain.
Officials imposed the six-month ban on Glitter after it informed monitoring authorities that it planned to travel through France to Spain.
The travel ban was approved by the Kent police last Thursday after they handed over evidence of Glitter's past convictions for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford's lowest criminal court in Kent, but was represented by lawyers from Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the court service said, "On Thursday, September 25, at Ashford's lowest criminal court, Kent police asked for an order that would prevent Mr Paul Gadd from crossing the border into France and Spain until March 25.
Paul Gadd did not attend in person."
Glitter, 64, has informed authorities that he wishes to travel abroad, as recorded in the sex offender register.
He must notify the authorities if he wants to travel abroad for more than three days.
They must also give the scheduled departure date to the police a week in advance.
If he fails to do so, he could be sentenced to five years.
Kent Police have announced that they will not be discussing individual cases of Glitter's possible trips around the county.
A spokesman for the Kent Police said, "The Kent Police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
From our point of view, it’s easier to track someone who stays in the UK because we have extensive systems that handle potential danger more effectively.
Protecting Kent residents is a top priority for the Kent Police and we are working hard to monitor the behavior of recorded sex offenders to minimise any risk to the public."
Glitter returned to Britain last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for the abuse of two girls aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, he flew to Bangkok, where he was scheduled to board a flight to London.
But he said he wasn't feeling well, and he refused to fly to London.
Thai authorities did not let him pass through passport control and he eventually flew to Hong Kong.
Chinese authorities also refused to allow him to enter, and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and immigration officials insisted on his return to Britain.
On 22 August, he finally arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 and stayed there while his attorney David Corker went to Uxbridge's lowest criminal court in West London, while at the same time Scotland Yard successfully requested an order requiring him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter had previously been jailed in the UK for four months for possessing child pornography.
A source from the Home Office said Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, is calm and glad that Glitter has been prevented from travelling to France and Spain.
"To capture the true character, I take pictures of the master outside the scene."
No heels, no frills, no costumes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, detached from the focus on interpretation - just so I can achieve a relaxed expression of a man or a woman.
On the one hand, an artist.
On the other - a man.
Inseparable, aside from privacy, in those moments far from the audience, one can then see an intimate gesture, the depth of a glimpse, or the passionate gesture of hands that are carefree because they are not about to step onto the stage.
The German G?nther Bauer alternates in the "Flamenco-people" theatricality of the performance with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer assembles a unique iconography of flamenco from various backgrounds.
The exhibition, which takes place as part of the Flamenco Photography Month (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca) program, "reflects the ever-increasing international importance of flamenco", the author says, explaining that "Flamenco-people" "can be any kind of people, but if you look at the photographs, you will find that these are not typical images of artists on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists able to bring passion, sadness, joy to the scene... and completely captivate the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
He wears his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of flamenco giants.
Enchanted by the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began a long journey in 1997 of portraying flamenco singers, guitarists, and dancers on a board camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classic photography.
Applying different stylistic means is contrary to the classic basis of the film and lends it a contemporary spirit, an idea that Bauer himself reflects even flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, but which does not cease to surprise and develop."
What draws the audience away is not the action of the dance, the singing or the play itself, but the personality and the character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we encounter the most essential, the spirit that manifests itself in the way of perception, being and experiencing, was and is a constant of work presented during these days in the El Fotómata Gallery.
This selection of nearly seventy photographed artists is shaped by well-known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become a kind of an anthology of flamenco and will soon receive a book edition containing exhibited portraits.
Two years ago, Bauer’s passion for portraiture led to the idea of repeating the idea at the “SportARTproject”.
Although their concept from "Flamenco-people" is different, the photographer admits that "to photograph people, to get to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a moment, whether longer or just short - that's my passion.
I think in photography, portraiture is the most difficult genre.
A person meets or clashes with people, personalities that he sometimes does not even know, or they give him just a few minutes for a photo shoot.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer I always try to realize my ideas."
A collection of contemporary flamenco portraits called "Flamenco-people" is exhibited at the El Fotómata Gallery in de la Mata 20, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
