The Ministry of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for drunk driving must install a system in his car that prevents him from starting the car when drunk or if he does not breathe.
The proposal became known in June this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Public Prosecutor’s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last for one year.
His goal is to return the driver behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to take a course in traffic re-education.
In addition to the National Traffic Safety Authority, the General Directorate of Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Technological Institute for Automotive Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of drivers charged more than once for drunk driving get behind the wheel again in this state.
Alcolock should prevent this from happening as it is a system connected to a vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe first or if a higher than permitted concentration of alcohol is detected.
Its price exceeds 1000 euros and it would have to be paid by the culprit himself.
A study conducted in the US in 2007 showed that offences against vehicles fitted with this device decreased by 65% during the first year of introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 people could be saved every year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it leads to a crime.
And in order to facilitate its implementation, since the legislation can be implemented in the usual way, the necessary adjustment of criminal provisions requires a change in the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although some industrial and public service vehicles have already been tested.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on the proposal of the PSOE (Spanish Workers’ Socialist Party), in which it is recommended to install this system on school buses, as is the case in France.
