Talking in Sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but the children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may startle you, but it's actually meaningless.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somnilocvia.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure many of you have heard that he was talking in his sleep at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with a high fever), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is not one single reason that explains its rise.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, nightmares, enuresis nocturna or sleepwalking, but it may not be the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often accompany very high fevers, stressful or exacerbated situations.
In any case, this is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or just the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests itself with great force, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if he has any problem that causes him great anxiety, and in this way he manifests himself.
We have said that it is a harmless disorder, so it is not treated only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
However, we can do this by keeping in mind a few very simple preventative measures, such as:
Try not to upset the baby too much before going to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who can relax, it is possible to use relaxation techniques that will help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the baby to sleep more peacefully.
When the somnilocius appears, try to keep calm.
Remind yourself that it is harmless to the child and that he will not remember anything from what happened the next day.
Helpful Hints
Don't wake him.
It is useless because he is not conscious and you interrupt his sleep.
Even when he speaks, he sleeps, and therefore rests.
Keep in mind that if your child seems to be very troubled several times in a row, it might be a good idea to seek advice or find out what is causing your child such anxiety.
If he understands what he is saying (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to interrogate him and extract information from him.
It won't do any good, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious, so he can arrange his thoughts.
In addition, you may hear what he says, but you don’t know what he is dreaming about, and therefore why, so be very careful about how you interpret the information and what conclusions you come to.
Never tell a child that you can ask him about his secret at night.
Not even for fun.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
Don’t worry, it’s not a bad thing, it’s just an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
