Interview - Blood That's Sure Again
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, rightly rejoiced as Héma-Québec became one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained public trust, which was seriously shaken after the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is widely known, the state blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Due to this drama and a wave of public outcry, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations that such a calamity not be repeated.
While Judge Krever delayed handing in the report, some provinces set in motion a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinea Committee stood up for this role.
After Gélineau and Krever's report, two contractors were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to manage Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society for supplying all provinces and both territories.
“When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system,” recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was disheartening.
Through continuous efforts to increase the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area over the following years, we have regained the trust of the public," he says, proudly adding that by the beginning of 2008 Héma-Québek was trusted by almost 94% of the Quebec population.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that “trust is something very fragile.”
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
“At the time, we saw many cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease,” says the woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread through the blood.
We have therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever-Gélineau report, according to which, when we do not know it and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, we need to take measures to eliminate it.
Thus, in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who had resided in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Several years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the precautionary principle made sense."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV emerged on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) to detect the presence of the virus itself in donor blood, rather than the presence of antibodies on which the tests were based.
NAT tests have reduced the deaf period between the time a patient is infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without their knowledge and without our being able to figure it out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
“In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone becomes infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product to occur.
I believe that today we can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion in complete peace of mind for healing," said Héma-Québek, the head of the Héma-Québek leadership.
“The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what disease-causing element may appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by insect bites.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that, in addition to the safe supply, Héma-Québec must also count on sufficient supply.
"Needs are growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive treatment of cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of eligible Quebecers."
Every healthy person at least 18 years of age, corresponding to the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people offering blood are not accepted because they carry AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have visited a country where mud fevers are raging, they are expelled for one year.
"With this 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be replenished as they age and are no longer able to donate blood.
But persuading people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life today is so unbridled that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Hema-Québek, which also administers the only public cord blood bank in Québek.
The umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, abounds in blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000th cord blood sample into the bank, and we expect to collect over 1,000 a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
“Some moms are disappointed that they don’t have access to it,” because Héma-Québec doesn’t have the resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all Québec hospitals.
