Letters - The Dishonored Land
It was Vic Toews, ex-minister of "justice" (o irony) in Harper's cabinet, who took the liberty of saying of Louise Arbour last summer that she represented a "shame" for Canada.
To dishonor a woman who has waged an unrelenting fight for justice and who deserves all our admiration says a lot about the Prime Minister's surroundings and Stephen Harper himself.
We have before us a government that is the only one among all the Western countries involved that has not brought back to its homeland its own citizen locked up in the Guantánamo concentration camp.
A government that doesn’t take into account that Omar Khadr was a young adolescent at the time when the actions that were being blamed on him were supposed to have taken place.
The only government that, despite signing the Geneva Convention, denies its word and lets a child soldier rot in inhumane conditions.
The only one who relies on a parody of justice to assess the defendant's guilt.
Recall that UNICEF, Amnesty International and especially the Association of Canadian Lawyers are advocating for the repatriation of Omar Khadr so that he can expect a fair trial in Canada.
The same government closes its eyes to torture: it cares little that this young man is psychologically destroyed henceforth, and undoubtedly permanently, after so many years of torment.
We don’t realize it, but we are witnessing a creeping erosion of our rights, our freedom, and our “democracy,” words that Harper so craves and that sound so empty out of his mouth.
The time has come when there is no more morality: it is possible to torture a Canadian citizen, mistreat him, imprison him at the will of the leader of the hitherto minority government (as will be the case after October 14...).
Many voters believe they will find salvation in the party that preaches Virtue, Law and Order: they do not see that this government has renounced what constituted the reputation and seriousness of our country.
Shame, Mr. Toews, on this renunciation, and not elsewhere.
Opinions - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In a September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world’s largest gold producer has launched prosecutions of three authors and a poor little publishing house for libel in order to spark a “transparent public debate” and demands six million from them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they judge not truthfulness, especially in the case of prosecution for libel, but law.
Unsurprisingly, Garver is completely oblivious to this crucial distinction.
Or is the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate, to bankrupt anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be ready to defend themselves and fight a very unbalanced battle with an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of a mining company.
Incidentally, tactics in these unsettled battles often consist of ruining the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that plugs the mouth of the opposing party and, moreover, frightens anyone who would dare to pursue the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of the matter to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate normally lies in the exchange of ideas, not the truncheons.
So mining companies have had to open up their books, their documentation, and establish a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and the funding of independent science teams that could shed light on the matter.
Barrick Gold, however, does not seem to have confidence in public opinion and promptly rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of the book Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public debate" and at the same time despise the views of the same public?
In the Vice President’s world, this word seems to refer only to high-paid lawyers, and not to all Canadians; that is a rather narrow concept of the term.
In a democracy, even libelers have the right to speak out.
Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - that the public that supports Noir Canada's authors and publishers does so primarily because they reject the brutal ways of the mining company.
The public is ready to hear and judge, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not within what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant is to be shut up (as part of its prosecution of the "public debate," Barrick, by the way, has just made an official appeal to the authors of Noir Canada to officially notify them to stop using the term...).
Aside from Garver’s surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university’s freedom of inquiry and truth-seeking, which is fundamental to any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss topics that the world’s rich don’t like without subjecting ourselves to repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have formed one if it followed the scientific standards used by Noir Canada authors.
He has a right to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s exaggerated lawsuit makes it clear that, despite what it claims, it has not the slightest desire to have a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to limit this type of unjustified prosecution.
