In particular, it foresees: better control of the elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms ensuring the repayment of deposited public money, new measures to capture the amount of houses seized for non-payment, as well as the right to monitor the amount of wages paid to executives of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi, and Representative of the Republicans at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, after the conclusion of a two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great strides in reaching an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Henry Paulson, a Bush administration official.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis that is taking place on Wall Street," he said.
"This is a crucial point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos, and disruption to Americans' everyday lives will be enormous," Rep. Judd Gregg said.
Over the past few hours, negotiations have taken a turn for fear of the effect another failure would have on investor sentiment.
The deadline was to open the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the U.S. presidency were invited to negotiate later, and both expressed their preference for the agreement, without neglecting to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such a last resort.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has added some measures to the deal, especially one designed to allow homeowners to retain their residence, as well as wage measures for state-saved labor leaders.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is no point in congratulating ourselves.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on the waves of television.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was polled by another station whether he would vote for the proposed plan, responded, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The coarse features I have read [show] that this is something that we will all have to digest and with which it will be possible to move forward.
To choose inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to buy up dubious claims and risky and unsaleable assets of US financial institutions with taxpayer money.
The plan comes after 14 months of a crisis unleashed by the bursting of the housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages, then shifted to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAAs), and resulted in a cash freeze and the disintegration of banks and financial institutions.
The collapse of the first draft deal last week was caused by Republican MPs.
Ever since the Democrats agreed that some of the “toxic” assets of companies in difficulty would only be guaranteed by the government, but would not be bought, it is believed that the impasse has been averted.
In an effort to reconcile opposing views in Congress, a measure was added stipulating that the government would be able to introduce new fees to help her get her deposit back if, as a result of the program, she would have to take losses for five years.
The new plan envisages a first deposit of $250 billion, to which another $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
A further $350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shares in the rescued companies, which will pay him dividends if he makes a profit, and which it will be able to resell when it’s all over.
The federal government will be able to delay the procedures for the seizure of real estate related to the loans covered by the plan, as well as set limits on the amount of remuneration and compensation paid to executives of the affected companies.
The plan's proponents would like to put it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have a green light.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against the project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It's pretty obvious that Washington can't hear you," said Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee.
“We have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
However, making money from taxpayers is not the solution.”
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed the "Skeptics Committee," presents the matter differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred distinguished professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us asking Congress not to rush too far and to look carefully at which path to take,” he said.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
Following the extraordinary meeting, three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for ?11.2 billion (US$16.3 billion).
Intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after French bank BNP Paribas announced it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapse since losing 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) due to the crisis of risky loans to buy real estate in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, is among Europe’s top 20 banks and top 10 insurers.
"We will not lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
“In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And that is what savers and households can appreciate in these uncertain times.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government appears to have begun nationalising another bank hit by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from the bank Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) were loans for the purchase of real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, Santander will buy the branches and client accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalised by the UK government since the start of the financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a socially engaged icon
His beauty with cyan eyes long represented his trump, according to others weakness.
Did this American actor with a charming smile break out of narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensibility, and undying talent that he possessed also distanced him from the power category that begets real stars.
What a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died Friday at his Connecticut ranch at the age of 83 as a result of lung cancer, and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less grandiose than Brando, whom he resembled and had long been his rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces beautiful babies.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and mother a Hungarian.
From these European roots, one of the famous faces of the American dream was born.
No exaggeration of the ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because it saw this whole country falling in love with self-made mana, a fighter in the Pacific War, wounded in battle, who studied acting at Yale in the early 1950s, then attended New York's Actor's Studio and celebrated triumph in theater, television, and early in film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a race car driver who placed second in the 24 Hours of Le Mans race in 1979, and a sexual symbol, despite the fact that he had been a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him, too, go the shady spots of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the fuss of his own show-business, which will forever remain mysterious to some extent.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman's passing this weekend has caused vertigo for movie lovers, while his big roles compete on the black screen of memories.
After him, more than half a century of the ever-changing American seventh art.
A charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) resurfaces in memory, a young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in A Cat on a Hot Roof, a 1958 adaptation of Tennessee Williams.
From a less distant past (1990) we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled at an advanced age by a marriage that did not meet all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, the tortured, violent, unforgettable delinquent from Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role reprised for James Dean after his death, which she made known to Newman in 1956.
A sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, the Oscar for Best Picture of 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiard player in Robert Rossen’s amazing The Hustler (1961), he will play the same character in Martin Scorsese’s The Color of Money, bringing him a single Oscar out of seven nominations in 1987.
This face wandering through the ages, it was he.
And him again.
In his professional career, different eras compete with each other.
The young know him mainly thanks to the cult Slap Shot George Roy Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
The fans met him again in 1994 at The Hudson's Proxy of the Coen Brothers.
He then ended his career playing the godfather of the Irish Mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes in 2003.
Unlike a few film legends who left the industry relatively early, Newman remained in the business for a long time, although he denounced Hollywood with its glamour, pomp, and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered it, not without humor, "a living challenge of underplaying", judging that he pushed too hard in his performances.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles came on a platter, the profession was not always so tender.
The first lovers, however, he played less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, rascals, and despondents, whose declension and rebellion were reflected in his perfect traits.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known aspects of his shy sensibility.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, gives a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
In 1984, he dedicated the film Harry and Son to his son Scott, whom he lost due to an overdose.
In a flurry of tributes to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade Robert Redford (played together in The Sting and in Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) lamented, "His presence made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of life, these are the main characteristics of a deceased actor.
Aside from his legendary career, he also leaves behind a great campaigner for civil rights, ecology, independent film, and an opponent of Hollywood’s decline.
We used to see his likeness on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, which may have seemed rather tasteless to us, although at first it was a gag.
However, the profits from the sale went to his Foundation for Difficult Childhood.
So Newman, rather than let himself be lulled by the glory, was engaged in society until the last moment.
He left a note with these words to his five daughters: "Always and to the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
It was an honor to be here.”
And for us, it was an honor to pursue the career of such a visionary and generous American artist.
After all, he is a model citizen.
What was produced at the Zuschlag & spol. invoice factory?
Soon, on October 8, the trial will begin in criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his associates.
The politician and his associates are accused, among other crimes, including forgery of documents, of fraud committed in the long term and systematically by a criminal organization, as a result of which extremely significant damage was caused.
According to the prosecutor's office, they used the money raised in public tenders for their own purposes and often documented the fulfillment of tasks with fictitious invoices.
The money from the state and self-government - totalling approximately 65 million forints - went partly to the treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The method also reported by the investigating authority was that the money raised in the tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no real consideration and never met the accepted commitments of the association.
According to the indictment, a large proportion of the invoices were fake.
The forms for these invoices came from the Józsefváros market, the round stamps were made in Kiskunhalasi.
The decision on the names of the companies to produce invoices was made, among other things, on a round trip along the northern shore of Lake Balaton, to which István Lados was sent by János Zuschlag.
According to his testimony, the first one had to look for pensions and restaurants.
In them, he applied for bills for his consumption, the model of which was then produced invoices submitted as part of public competitions announced by, among others, the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs, and the Municipality of the capital.
István Lados and his partner András ?ri, who, according to our information, most often wrote the reports needed to obtain subsidies, exhibited the invoices.
During his "study trip", Lados visited one of the cellars.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and his associates in 2003, the restaurant catered for the 90-member Biztos Pont group.
However, according to the head of the company, so many people would not fit into this device at once.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 was full of formal and factual errors to a foundation called Jobb J?v?ért, later Egy?tt and Harmadik Évezredért.
The guest house in Badacsonytomaji had only three rooms, no more than ten people could not sleep in it one night, yet one hundred and thirty guests were listed on the invoice.
Fillers of forms with a rich imagination, however, overstated it even when they listed on the documents a company dedicated to the hospitality industry - Pigal s. r. o., in whose accounting according to the information provided to the Public Prosecutor's Office documents sounding in the name of Jobb J?v?ért and Hoppá did not even figure.
Mr Farkas told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor’s office and shown invoices, he immediately knew they were fake documents.
"Our business name and our tax number were stamped in the wrong place."
In addition to the formalities, he said, they did not agree to accommodate 100 people because they only had 11 rooms that did not have such a large capacity.
In addition, food was also indicated on the invoice, and their restaurant has not worked for a long time.
Zealous invoice producers were also not convinced that the Budapest travel agency they were looking for only organizes foreign trips, and they foolishly listed the invoice with cash payment, which also did not coincide with the company’s invoicing practice, as a travel mediation service in Hungary.
In addition, as the investigation revealed, VAT was also included in the document, although the organisation of travel to countries outside the European Union was exempted from VAT.
In the four documents issued to Jobb J?v?ért by Hotel Révf?l?p s.r.o., the company’s activities were not covered by the 25 % but by the 15 % VAT, in addition to which the hotel employees issued only printed invoices, but the invoice was handwritten.
In addition, the "publishers" spoiled the invoice by stating that one company, as it turned out thanks to an investigation by the Public Prosecutor's Office, was engaged in the transport of goods by road, which the company originally based on investment advice did not carry out.
Moreover, the fact that the invoices issued to the Egy?tt and Harmadik Évezredért Foundation and the XXI Századi Kulturális Egyes?let and Biztos Pont associations are false has also been revealed due to formal deviations - not in accordance with the invoice format and the wrong stamp.
As in the case of Ravenna k. s. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, their representatives denied that they had issued the invoices.
For example, the forgers did not notice that the company HIB s. r. o. from Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time (2001), when a group from the Fiatal Városért association was eating there, which is why, according to our information, the company’s liquidation commissioner also denied that he would issue the paper.
Invoices were consciously
The second group of invoicers are those who knew to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Esély Budapestért Foundation has issued accounts for about four million forints to the Harmadik Évezredért Foundation at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták organization.
According to the indictment, the head of Collab s. r. o. was forced to issue a fictitious account by one of the accused Ludovic Gy?rfi.
Biogate s. r. o. also cooperated with Zuschlage and its partners, currently in liquidation, which supplied Jobb J?v?ért and Atlasz and V?r?sfeny with invoices worth around five million forints in 2003, which did not involve any real economic activity.
