While the perpetrators of economic crimes, who have done much greater harm than they have paid, are free to walk or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their homes, he does not have this option.
Psychology of trumping: why do we spend more money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed to researchers in the fields of neurology and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to fall behind in eBay auctions, so they would rather pay too high a price.
The research used an experimental auction to try to map the pattern of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a live auction, where active brain regions were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method.
In both games, participants could win money, but when playing at an auction, an important element of which is to trump the other side, the whole located under the cerebral cortex, called striatum, began to work intensively while losing.
This brain area, among many other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the unscrewing of the price can be explained by an effort to avoid a sharp striatum reaction.
To support their theory, members of the research team from the ranks of economists conducted a financial cross-sectional survey.
There were three groups bidding against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the other group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but lost the money in the event of a loss.
So the difference between the two groups was that one was highlighted as a win and the other as a loss.
However, the anti-loser group were willing to go higher than the control and the “winner” group, confirming the neurologist’s hypothesis.
"These results cannot be deduced from any pre-existing economic theory.
Until now, they have explained the phenomena observable in the auctions of the joys of victory and avoidance of risk.
Neurological imaging methods have helped us resolve the discrepancy between the two theories, and now we have a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is the leading cause of death.
The number of home cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 of them are treated. The reason for this is that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective term for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, which are characterized by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the causative agents of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Depending on the causative agent of the disease, hepatitis A and E spread through the digestive tract (for example, infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood and body fluids viruses (semen, vaginal secretions, saliva).
In any case, travelers should protect themselves by vaccinating against the A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against the C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, nausea.
After that, jaundice forms on the skin and whites of the eyes, pale stools and darkens urine. Treatment can last as long as two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from the more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected patients is treated with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most people don’t even know about their disease, the causative agent of the disease destroys liver cells insidiously, and so the first symptoms occur in many cases in 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention is very important, the implementation of regular screening.
In three groups, the disease occurs much more often than average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated number of people worldwide infected with chronic hepatitis C is 200 million.
Since the disease can already be proven by routine laboratory tests, a person should contact his or her general practitioner if he or she notices any symptoms of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body to prevent infection and prevent the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized by organizations representing the sick worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God doesn’t hurt so much?
According to recent research, belief in God works as a kind of analgesic that could have eased the death of already Catholic martyrs.
Scientists from Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment, examining how the belief in a god affects the perception of pain in a person, reports the British newspaper Telegraph.
In a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and an equal number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to eliminate much of the pain.
Thanks to a technique that examines the human brain in detail, it has also been shown that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The research is the first in a series of studies involving scholars, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The test was carried out precisely by attaching a sparking tool to the left hand of the test subject, which gave off electric shocks.
The researchers asked participants to observe two paintings: Sassoferrata’s 17th-century Virgin Mary and Leonardo da Vinci’s 15th-century lady with an ingret.
The authors of the research hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would evoke a certain state of piety in the faithful, while Da Vinci’s image was chosen because it was not very different from the first and it gave them a calming impression.
Subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time, they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive portions, while separately viewing the image with a religious or general theme.
Catholics said they felt “safe” when they saw the Virgin Mary, as if they had been “taken care of” and “calmed down, filled with peace.”
When viewing a religious painting, they said they felt 12 percent less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any strongly impressive image even in atheists, just need to find the right photo.
"We would have to find an image that they would perceive very positively, from the position of mother or father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“Practicing faith should and in many cases will change our personality,” Wright said.
After such great results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on the regulation of the pain of believers if they were shown a Madonna by Leonardo or a painter of a similar caliber.
Would looking at a quality Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
You are what you share.
On their tenth birthday, Google can say that people can find it in their pocket at least as well as in the sky above their heads; they know where they have been on vacation, what specialist examinations they go to, and what interests them.
According to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's executives, that's still not enough.
However, when it comes to skeptics who parallel Orwellian dark visions, the very nature of Web 2.0 is not clear to them.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, which is necessary for Google’s founders to stick to their original intent: “Let’s organize all the information in the world!”
According to a Google representative, even after ten years of world-class work, the company is only at the beginning of working with all the information.
When asked what would be five years from now, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "what should I do tomorrow?" or "what kind of work would be right for me?" -- but software won't be able to answer those seemingly simple questions until they know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are well aware that during Internet searches, search words are accurately captured, as well as from which IP address they were searched and to which pages the searchers moved after searching.
Thanks to the Personalized Search service launched two years ago, users can, for example, save their browsing history, look back at what they were looking for and clicked on, which in the long term generates findings tailored to them - the same logic will be based on Recommendations, through which the system will offer products and services based on the previously mentioned and retained preferences.
What if my data is used against me, what if someone looks at what I do? - ask users who are afraid of looking at Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, the extent of the potential power represented by the company is rather threatening; the counter-reaction does not cause Internet users to feel guilty, fear of punishment, desire for freedom, or even revolt against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all search terms are not only captured, but can also be issued to a third party in justified cases, in such legal cases, the personal rights of Internet users do not protect anything.
Perhaps the best-known example of this was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Orkut community pages set up through it.
But Internet users worried about personal rights could take a breather in May, when the company, in conjunction with the EFF, successfully proved its truth in a dispute with the FBI: Google must not be forced by any article of the Constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully scrambled nearly 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms, which it obtained in reference to a strengthening of the child protection law passed years ago, yet it failed to get lists of individual users’ search items, or complete lists of web pages and keywords, covering a period of two months.)
The view of Google is so contradictory: it is being flogged by those who are afraid of providing their personal data, because they feel that their intimate sphere and private life will be harmed by using Google services, and they oppose it with the revolt that belongs to multinational companies with a conservative image.
Meanwhile, America’s geek culture and its wild offshoot, rallying around enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, appearing in many countries, sees it as a new generation of big business, a “corporation that’s now booming,” unlike its rival Microsoft, which is seen as a world conqueror because of Windows, though both are fighting for the same goals.
This may be due to the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require an identification code from its users and does not want them to pay for their applications; an open, free and constantly fresh source of information, and a package of programs seems much more accessible, more youthful, "cooler" than the practice of an official software giant.
However, this may also be due to the fact that geeks accurately understand the very problematic relationship between the Internet and personal rights, which brought with it one of the most common keywords of recent years: web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, about deliberately leaving our footprints behind and using the communication channels we have, and although their scope is different for everyone, the essence remains the same: we show ourselves.
The average young person can keep a profile on several community sites from Facebook to Xang, which they can easily connect with other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm app that records their music, all of which they can then connect to navigation systems, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, as well as write a blog on which their latest photo galleries will automatically appear.
We can read about a lot of exemplary cases, from which it emerges: a girlfriend in the morning, looking at a flood of photos of her mutual friends, easily figures out who her sly friend spent the evening with, or the company can fire her employee just because she describes her honest opinion about the top management in her blog: one thing is for sure, the concept of private life has been completely reconsidered today.
One who lives an online life consists of what he shows of himself, so we could define the basic thesis behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least avoid the Google monopoly, has the option (starting with Scroogle, which uses Google’s search system, however, deliberately leaves no trace).
For example, a significant number of people don’t register on community sites to avoid being found. Google’s online applications, from text editor to photo editor and news portal, can be exchanged for alternative versions that are not connected to giant server parks and that do not build the best possible profile from us.
Public opinion is not secretly waiting for Google to show its teeth.
