Intelligent car imitates the flight of a bumblebee
What would be the best method to develop technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitation detectors of obstacles occurring in the world of nature?
For example, with bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprise project, presented at the CEATEC trade fair in Japan, was inspired by Nissan engineers to build a new generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has engineered a biomimetic BR23C robotic control system, a robotic minicar that is equipped with bee features, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
“During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which actually closely resembles our safety protective packaging,” said Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of Technology PR and R&D.
Compound eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eye, engineers went for the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters ahead of BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into a collision avoidance operation.
The obstacle is captured in a fraction of a second, then the robotized car begins to imitate the movements of the bee and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent a collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this pull-out manoeuvre takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and inmost layer of the safety protective package, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process has to reflect what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered by bees during avoidance, only the possibility of rotational movement, acceleration and deceleration was applied in the case of a robotic car.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, an instinctive, intelligent response is important, not the ability to process, much less store data.
This mechanism only needs to process and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need for it to store and react using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it constantly uses only memory of a few kilobytes in size.
It does not need memory with giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step in the development of an immediate avoidance technology that Nissan predicts could enter production vehicles within a decade.
Another option may be to connect the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the motorist to the specified final destination after avoiding obstacles in the way.
