The $700 billion bailout bill, which is to be split into several instalments and aims to buy back low-quality bank loans, is already in writing.
Half of the amount will be used in the first round.
After further talks, which ended just after midnight on Saturday, Congressional officials reached an agreement in a few days of debate over a $700 billion bailout package.
"We have made significant progress," Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic Speaker of the House of Representatives, said in a statement.
Both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain, also supported the compromise on the package.
Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said of the compromise's outcome: "The program will work and be effective, but further steps need to be taken."
The written form of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. Washington time (that is, Monday at 2 a.m. Central European Time), but it did not cause any particular rise in the stock market.
The bill, which will be called the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, will be voted on by the House of Representatives on Monday, followed by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday night, after which news of the deal was also welcomed at the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made at night and greatly appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
After all, the program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend $700 billion on low-quality mortgage-backed securities all at once.
It is now possible to spend up to half of $700 billion in the first round by using $250 billion immediately after Congress is expected to decide the matter on Monday, with the Treasury buying mortgage-backed securities that are rated as low-quality, with the fate of the remaining $100 billion depending on the president’s decision.
The program will be overseen by a special committee of which the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank will also be a member.
Spending the second half of $700 billion will depend on the next Congressional decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy out low-quality loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, or other "poisonous" loans.
Purchases can take place within the auctions and directly, the competent representatives of the Ministry said.
The law will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance program in which the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee for funds representing a cause for concern, for which the companies will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of expected damages.
As Henry Paulson said, the bill provides the necessary funds to meet the urgent demands of the U.S. financial system, whether it’s to make large-scale purchases of bad funds, to insure them, or to prevent systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the major financial institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed."
On the contrary, bank bosses who are in trouble and waiting for the help of the state can count on the government to reduce their severance pay - which is simply called a "golden parachute" in overseas slang.
Their payouts will be limited only in certain cases, moreover, these restrictions will depend on the method of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction basically means that if the Ministry buys in the auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on the gold parachutes, unless the fallen bank directors are sent straight to retirement.
In the case of a direct buyback of low-quality loans, the government will aggressively intervene in order not to exaggerate the money for the leadership.
It is necessary to add that the existing gold-fall contracts will not change, the restriction applies only to new contracts, which is supposed to be an additional incentive to participate in the program.
"This is the first time in U.S. history that there will be statutory restrictions on CEO compensation," said Barney Frank, chairman of the House Financial Services Committee.
In addition, the state will have the right to acquire a stake in the banks participating in the program, which will reduce the risk of taxpayers, because once the economy, and with it the rescued bank, gets back on its feet, they can also profit from this transaction.
In the next five years, the president will have to submit a bill to Congress setting out how the expected losses from the financial sector can be repaid to taxpayers.
Of course, there were voices of doubt on both sides.
“This is not what the American people asked us to do, it’s not what will protect taxpayers’ dollars,” said Rep. Darrell Issa, a Republican congressman from California.
His Ohio Democratic colleague, Mary Kaptur, said that those responsible for the Wall Street collapse had urged the legislation.
Industrial prices continue to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry rose 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, compared to 12.9 percent in August 2007, the Central Bureau of Statistics reported.
Export sales prices in the industry were 1.1 percent higher compared to July 2008, down 3.9% year-on-year.
Production prices in industry were 0.7% higher as a cause of domestic and export price changes compared to the previous month, up 3.2% year-on-year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased only minimally compared to the previous month, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sector also increased slightly, by 0.1 percent, compared to July.
The biggest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8%), mainly due to a month-on-month increase in the production of bag and saddlery products by 4.6% and in the production of footwear by 2.5%.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical materials and products sector (1.6 percent).
Price cuts occurred in the oil processing sector (1.4 percent), the production of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimal extent - in the woodworking sector (0.1 percent).
Prices in the paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other manufacturing industries, we have seen price increases of between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water generation and distribution sector, which has a significant impact on domestic sales of the industry, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the continuing increase in gas prices, which has been officially set since July 1.
In the 12-month comparison of domestic sales in individual sectors of the processing industry, prices increased the most in the oil processing sector (32.4%).
In the metalworking industry, there was a 13.2 percent increase in prices for food products, beverages and tobacco products, which has a decisive weight.
Prices fell in the textiles and textile products (2.5%) and electrical machinery and equipment (0.3%) sectors.
In other manufacturing industries, the price growth rate was between 0.6% and 9.1%.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing sector increased by 10.2% over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sector exceeded those of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In terms of division by industry focus, the highest monthly price increase (0.7%) in the sectors concerned with the production of tangible assets was reflected in domestic sales in August.
In the consumer goods industries, prices rose by 0.3 percent, in the energy processing and downstream industries, prices did not change compared to the previous month.
The largest increase in prices compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in the energy processing and downstream sectors (16.8%) in August 2008.
In the consumer goods industries, we recorded a price increase of 6.8 percent, while for tangible assets, prices fell by 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products, measured in forints, rose 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, down 3.9 percent in a 12-month comparison.
Our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro in one month, 7.1 percent against the dollar, 7.5 percent against the euro in August 2007, and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
