MP3 Players Charged, Put Hearing at Risk
Listening to loud music for extended periods of time and using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
According to a European Commission announcement published today, quoting the opinion of the Committee for the Science of Health Risks, which has recently emerged and has been identified (Csrseri) by the EU, in an official report circulated widely in Brussels.
"From this scientific point of view - we read in the notes - 5-10% of those who listen to music using portable music devices for at least five years, more than an hour a day and keep the device at high volume, risk permanent loss of hearing ability."
“It worries me that such a large number of young people who use often portable musical instruments and mobile phones at high acoustic levels can unknowingly damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” admits Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific findings - continues the lead - indicate a clear risk and need to be acted upon quickly.
Most importantly, we need to encourage consumers and make this information public.
We must continue to re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific finding so that they become fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to investigate this problem, given the high use of portable musical instruments and the growing number of young people exposed to noise of this origin.
"Scientists confirm that there is a need to worry and now the European Commission, together with the other members and the parties that raised the issue, will examine what measures could possibly be put in place to better protect children and young people from being exposed to noise caused by portable musical instruments and similar devices."
There is already a safety European standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that may be caused by overexposure to similar forms of noise.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by looking for solutions such as reducing the level and duration of exposure.
According to the EU Scientific Committee, users of portable music devices who use loud music (more than 89 decibels) for just five hours a week will exceed the currently applicable limits for maximum permitted workplace noise.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for an extended period of time risk permanent hearing loss after five years.
This problem should affect 5-10% of users of such devices, and their amount can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
