Elites in Danger
This phenomenon became apparent a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion rescue plan put forward by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis is tearing apart the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, its milder, federal-agency and business-community-friendly, and its new soul, which is conservative, hostile to “those from Washington” and the world of finance, especially strong in states in the middle and south.
A soul that has arrogantly manifested itself in the vote I was talking about at the beginning..
But this just quoted thing is just an example of the changes, the big changes, that the current economic earthquake is already showing: not just in the United States, but in the whole West, and maybe not just here.
Both in the US and in Europe, this crisis seems to act as an accelerator of phenomena that have been incubated for a long time, which are solidifying and finally coming to light in the new climate.
The first of these phenomena is actualization, an extraordinary revival of the market, a double category of State-power in relation to a certain renationalization of economics.
Indeed, the crisis is a crisis of banking financial institutions, which, of course, have strong ties abroad, but in which, above all, the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state, are included to the greatest extent.
Which has also created a political problem for those who run it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are, among other things, voters.
In short, the crisis appears economically global, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationality seems to be substantially out of the question, or that it has nothing much to add: the obvious evidence has been given by the European Union, which is divided as always between different interests and different national strategies, and which is unable to choose a single common political line.
And so everyone is waiting for the intervention of the government of each individual state, rescue plans, market recovery, new rules and, above all, the distribution of funds: the moment we get into distress, only states have the economic means, the amount of financial resources, to be able to try to put everything in order.
And they also possess the necessary resources and authorizations to use them: two sources of immense value, under certain circumstances that perhaps no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose of to a similar degree.
Indeed, this new emphase, which the crisis places on the state-national element, is in full accord with the growing importance which the latest economic advances attempt to attribute to one factor closely connected with it: territorial jurisdiction.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the kingdom of a network, increasingly sophisticated technology, immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to rule the world, all of a sudden we realized that our future would have to deal more and more with such little immaterial things as water, grain, oil.
All things, who would say, can be transported from one place on the earth to another, but in any case they are connected, absolutely, to a limited space, a territory.
So who will become their ruler, certainly has much more cards up his sleeve than who is not, and who has the misfortune to live in a place without grain, without oil, and without water.
I come to the second news, which, however, foresees a turning point.
Those who speak of territory, state, government, inevitably speak of politics, that is, of leadership.
Given the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena appear to be emerging.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritarian leadership, a request for someone who can take the situation.
On the other hand, there has been a wave of discrediting of existing leaderships, especially economic ones, which have proved equally unsatisfactory and full of dark places.
And together, something even deeper and in a sense disturbing: the discredit, the impatience, the sense of incompetence and absence that is trying to dominate the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries.
Indeed, it seems that convictions are becoming more and more widespread among the broad masses of the population, rather than their actions being the same as the ideas of the hitherto popular elite, as their way of feeling and being, as their culture in the true sense of the word, that the elite has already surpassed its time and is indifferent to the views of the majority.
The demand for leadership simply feeds one branch from the underground, but a strong movement for the removal of the ruling classes and the traditional political order is manifested in unexpected electoral “resistances” or unexpected changes in collective moods in recent and recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the fall of the Labour Party in Great Britain, to the revolt of US congressmen against Bush (and perhaps what to do with it).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their ceremonies, their newspapers, their accredited intelligence, some would say their format, are having more and more problems to understand, that is, to represent, which, not as of today, is being created in the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is getting stronger again, growing, potentially too loud.
Before this, it would be an exaggeration to speak of a permanent “mass rebellion”.
But we can't say that it means keeping your eyes open.
