The painting, offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore, successfully documents what is happening in large Italian urban centers as well as rural towns.
The process of limiting cinemas, the birth of large multi-halls in the suburbs, and the subsequent demise of mono-halls in the central zones of cities is one of the events that seems inevitable and irreversible, but also has all the hallmarks of a true cultural crime.
“It’s like losing a friend, a friend with whom we shared a part of our journey and a lot of emotions,” says director of New Cinema Paradiso, a film that won Tornator an Oscar and a grand jury prize at Cannes 20 years ago, and who told the poetry of a village cinema and sadness over a way of life that the cinema may have lost forever.
The values obtained by Anec, the main association of operators, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional tip closed their doors, and the highest bill was paid primarily by the halls in the most important cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Torino, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures, Emilia-Romagna comes first with the loss of 82 cinema halls, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
