When energy is born from the waves, the big ones come into play.
It is an infinite deposit that covers more than 70% of the Earth’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new sources of inexhaustible energy that have caught the eye of colossus like Chevron, who is now trying to lay hands on these sources.
The possibility of generating energy from sea movements has been studied for more than a century, and in the 1970s, in the context of the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell around 1980, the idea of using marine energy went away. But now environmental organizations and a new increase in the price of oil gave the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London stated in 2007 that approximately 15 percent of the world's electricity consumption could be covered by the use of ocean waves.
That would be twice the amount of energy currently produced in nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are currents and tides.
Giants are attacking.
The company that bet on marine energy was Enersis, which agreed in 2005 to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When this intention was announced, it seemed like a huge revolutionary step.
After two years of betting on marine energy, more and more companies are betting on marine energy rather than traditional energy.
"Chevron studies ocean energy technology - spoke a spokesperson for one company that is linked to the United States oil colossus in the economic daily Wall Street Journal - and they are thinking about the possibility of working with us".
The cooperation we are considering concerns obtaining permission from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary for the launch of a marine energy project in Alaska.
We cannot underestimate this signal, especially when we consider that it is in Alaska that the US continues to produce oil, and recently President Bush has come up with a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are following the trail of marine energy, and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, show increasing interest, according to observers.
Technology needs to be developed.
Experts are talking about technology that is still in its infancy, because it is not known what impact the use of marine energy will have on the environment.
So far, the facilities in Portugal and some in Scotland are of small dimensions and do not seem to cause major ecosystem problems.
For greater energy production, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a greater impact on the environment.
The methods are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of scares that are interconnected with each other.
The strength of the waves that move up and down with the buoys is changed with the help of cylinders and cylinders to the hydraulic pressure inside these buoys.
The pressure spins the turbine, which supplies power to the generator.
The energy is coming ashore through submarine cables.
At the moment, there are four such devices in the project phase, which are only waiting for federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for military purposes.
Verdant Power already generates power for its shopping mall and car park by using six submarine turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of water during high tide causes the turbines to rotate, which feed the generator.
Verdant said they have a long list of clients waiting for necessary authorizations to use this energy.
After the waves, after the tides, after the tides.
Of particular interest at this point is the potential for tides, say the Institute for Electric Energy Research.
Although it is an incoherent factor, tides are more predictable than wind, sun or waves, and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
Countries like New York, Maine, and Alaska, along with other coastal states, have already invested $7.5 million in 2008 and predicted investments of up to $35 million for 2009.
